Slobodan Kačar (born September 15, 1957) is a retired <a href="/wiki/Bosnian_Serb" title="Bosnian Serb" class="mw-redirect">Bosnian Serb</a> <a href="/wiki/Boxing" title="Boxing">boxer</a>, born in <a href="/wiki/Peru%C4%87ica" title="Perućica">Perućica</a> near <a href="/wiki/Jajce" title="Jajce">Jajce</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bosnia_and_Herzegovina" title="Bosnia and Herzegovina">Bosnia and Herzegovina</a>, then <a href="/wiki/SFR_Yugoslavia" title="SFR Yugoslavia" class="mw-redirect">SFR Yugoslavia</a>. He won the <a href="/wiki/Olympic_medalists_in_boxing" title="Olympic medalists in boxing" class="mw-redirect">Light Heavyweight Gold medal</a> for <a href="/wiki/Yugoslavia" title="Yugoslavia">Yugoslavia</a> at the <a href="/wiki/1980_Summer_Olympics" title="1980 Summer Olympics">1980 Summer Olympics</a>. In the same year, Kačar was named as. He is the younger brother of boxer <a href="/wiki/Tadija_Ka%C4%8Dar" title="Tadija Kačar">Tadija Kačar</a>, who won a silver medal at the <a href="/wiki/1976_Summer_Olympics" title="1976 Summer Olympics">1976 Summer Olympics</a>.
Kačar turned pro in 1983 and won his first 21 fights, including a victory over <a href="/wiki/Eddie_Mustafa_Muhammad" title="Eddie Mustafa Muhammad">Eddie Mustafa Muhammad</a> to capture the vacant IBF Light Heavyweight Title. Kačar lost his next fight, a defense against <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Czyz" title="Bobby Czyz">Bobby Czyz</a> in 1986 via 5th round TKO. Kačar retired the next year with a record of 22–2–0.
